          "body": "Hosea 9 opens at a harvest festival — almost certainly Sukkot, the Feast of Tabernacles, when the year's grain and wine were in. The rejoicing was intense and public, 'like the nations.' That phrase is the indictment. Israel was not merely celebrating a good harvest; she was celebrating it with the nations' religious forms — the fertility rites performed at Canaanite threshing floors where sacred prostitution secured (supposedly) agricultural blessing. The 'harlots' earnings' (*etnan*, the fee paid to a cult prostitute) that Israel loved at every threshing floor (9:1) are the precise inversion of covenant worship. She has been paying Baal for grain while YHWH provided it. The irony of the sentence is surgical: the threshing floor and winepress will not feed them, and the new wine will fail (9:2). The instrument of apostasy becomes the instrument of famine. The climactic question of 9:5 — 'What will you do on the day of the appointed festival?' — is not a pastoral inquiry. It is a taunt. There will be no festival to attend; Egypt and Assyria will host their next gathering."
