          "title": "The silenced watchman — prophecy mocked and snared (9:7-9)",
          "body": "Hosea 9:7 contains one of the most dramatic announcements in the Hebrew prophets: 'The days of punishment have come, the days of retribution have come; let Israel know this!' The perfect tense in Hebrew signals that the announcement is not a warning of what is coming but a declaration that the sentence has arrived. And within the same verse, the culture's response to prophetic warning is quoted: 'The prophet is a fool, the inspired man is demented.' This is not Hosea's verdict on false prophets — it is Israel's verdict on Hosea himself and on every true prophet she has rejected. Verse 8 deepens the tragedy: the prophet was appointed as Ephraim's watchman with God, a sentinel whose whole purpose was to see the approaching threat and warn the city. But a snare of the fowler is laid in all his ways — the very man God appointed to protect Israel has been turned into prey by the people he was sent to guard. The house of his God — the religious establishment of Bethel and Dan — is saturated with hostility toward the true prophetic word. By 9:9 the diagnostic reaches its historical benchmark: 'They have gone deep in depravity as in the days of Gibeah.' Gibeah is the Judges 19-20 reference — the night when a Levite's concubine was gang-raped to death and an entire tribe nearly annihilated in civil war. That is the measure of where Israel now stands. The warning section closes with the same two verbs that will govern the chapter's whole argument: 'He will remember their iniquity, He will punish their sins.'"
